04812nam a22005655i 9780822389200DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223892007 a10.1515/97808223892002doi  a(DE-B1597)554552  a(OCoLC)1170205594  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ1233b.C36 2008 7aSOC0280002bisacsh1 aCarrillo Rowe, Aimee, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPower Lines :bOn the Subject of Feminist Alliances /cAimee Carrillo Rowe. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tPREFACE: Color in My Lines -- tINTRODUCTION: On the Subject of Feminist Alliances -- t1. BE LONGING. Toward a Feminist Politics of Relation -- t2. BRIDGE INSCRIPTIONS. Toward a Methodology of Feminist Alliance -- t3. ‘‘WOMEN’’ ON THE INSIDE Whiteness, Heterosociality, and the Subject of Feminist Alliances -- t4 Zero-Sum Feminism: On the Interface between ‘‘Feminism’’ and ‘‘Alliances’’ -- t5. POWER LINES Toward a Feminism of Radical Belonging -- tEPILOGUE Pilgrimage -- tAPPENDIX A Solicitation Letter -- tAPPENDIX B Interview Questions -- tNOTES -- tWORKS CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLike the complex systems of man-made power lines that transmit electricity and connect people and places, feminist alliances are elaborate networks that have the potential to provide access to institutional power and to transform relations. In Power Lines, Aimee Carrillo Rowe explores the formation and transformative possibilities of transracial feminist alliances. She draws on her conversations with twenty-eight self-defined academic feminists, who reflect on their academic careers, alliances, feminist struggles, and identifications. Based on those conversations and her own experiences as an Anglo-Chicana queer feminist researcher, Carrillo Rowe investigates when and under what conditions transracial feminist alliances in academia work or fail, and how close attention to their formation provides the theoretical and political groundwork for a collective vision of subjectivity.Combining theory, criticism, and narrative nonfiction, Carrillo Rowe develops a politics of relation that encourages the formation of feminist alliances across racial and other boundaries within academia. Such a politics of relation is founded on her belief that our subjectivities emerge in community; our affective investments inform and even create our political investments. Thus experience, consciousness, and agency must be understood as coalitional rather than individual endeavors. Carrillo Rowe’s conversations with academic feminists reveal that women who restrict their primary allies to women of their same race tend to have limited notions of feminism, whereas women who build transracial alliances cultivate more nuanced, intersectional, and politically transformative feminisms. For Carrillo Rowe, the institutionalization of feminism is not so much an achievement as an ongoing relational process. In Power Lines, she offers a set of critical, practical, and theoretical tools for building and maintaining transracial feminist alliances.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFeminism and higher education. 0aFeminismxPolitical aspects. 0aLesbian feminism. 0aMinority women. 0aRace relations. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822389200zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822389200423Co